Jericho Giles BOT 10-Feb-20 04:38 PM
A moment later there was the shimmer of light which indicated someone beaming in, but instead of the flecks of light being golden they were solely silver. Two figures materialised; a Trill man and a dog. The man's outfit was refined; navy double-breasted jacket and suit seeming immaculate, oxfords polished, a white scarf draped around his neck... But perhaps the outfit was just an attempt to distract from how horribly pale and sickly he looked, to the extent that even his trill spots were washed out. His mess of white-blond hair was flattened... And he was dripping wet for some reason. The collie dog was the same; beneath the harness which marked it as a service dog its fur was drenched what must be salt-water, judging by the smell. Almost immediately upon materialising in the man ran a hand through his hair, pushing it back out of his face. He glanced and gave a nod to the group who all seemed very uncomfortable standing there in front of Xaav. "Goodness, you lot, I'm surprised you haven't broken anything with that strained posture," he mused whilst rummaging around in a pocket, and then extracted a cigarette and a modern-style lighter. "Finally, dry land... Didn't think I was going to see it for quite some time." Holding the cigarette between two fingers, he lit it with the lighter's flame which, for some reason, was blue.

Fleet Admiral Phenna Ephrix BOT 12-Jun-20 09:17 PM
Phenna had been on her way to a meeting with the president himself when there was a sudden global sensation that the world had been thrown into disarray. Surprise, anger, unbridled fear- it was quite the change from how everyone had been perfectly content only moments before. It was then that she was informed that being broadcast live were reports of the president being assassinated – and that Woystusyu had somehow broken out. She had no recollection of getting to Command. Actively processing that sort of thing was not required during an event of this scale; everything was put into crisis management instead. To the front lines the MACOs were attempting to break into the main structure of Command – Starfleet were attempting to prevent this. Casualties were being dragged through the crowd underneath the phaserfire. It was here, typically, that she could be found, telepathic sight focussed on only the casualties who were brought behind the lines. Someone else was triaging today. She couldn’t see the colours to tag them. “Blood transfusion required, transport as soon as possible.” Onto the next. “You need a line in, administering adrenaline immediately.” And the next; a MACO officer. They were treating both here, as medical tended to do. No matter what side you were on you still deserved aid. “A priority one alpha? I-gel in, high-flow oxygen on, check their sats, cortical stimulator, someone get a hypospray of-“ That surprisingly calm voice was cut off as someone suddenly pushed her closer to the ground – out of the way of a bolt from a phaser rifle. Neither seeing nor hearing the phaserfire was quite the disadvantage. She really wasn’t equipped for fieldwork nowadays. “-5ccs of cordrazine, please, and thank you to whoever that was ...They’re borderline asystolic, we really need that hypospray now, please...“
There was no time to ponder on what had happened – no time to consider how Woystusyu had gotten out, why people were following her orders. All there was time to consider was the casualties piling up, how to best treat them, and how unfair all of this was on the Federation. The people did not deserve this all over again.

Nymeria’s words, of course, had gone unheard. Telepathic sight pinged straight through the figures instead off of them – it was like their own matter and composition was breaking up into nothingness. The air went cold as they fully disappeared, their auras lost to the void. Although she couldn’t see it her hands had began to do the same, breaking down into specs of light. This was not the way she had expected to die, nor was this the time… After all of their contingencies and formation of a dedicated council of Admiralty – it still hadn’t been enough. She sighed and ‘looked’ out at the carnage beyond… And then to the Starfleet officers fighting back, ready to defend the Federation and its principles to their last breath. A slow inhale and she closed her eyes, focussing one last time. “Good luck,” her voice echoed in the minds of the officers assembled there. “And be safe. Everything will be alright in the end.” The lilt of her voice faded alongside her physical form: giving way to those small glimmers of light, swept away by the wind.
